snippet.textDisplay: Anyone know if putting on a headspacer and studs would help in a build like this? snippet.textDisplay:
there a price that cannot be put on the pride of being able to slap youreself on the chest and tell someone : "I made /build that !"


there are ways to get it cheaper , like buying a or parts from an unfinished project , maibe more than one , that can have the parts included like the aftermarked ecu for a fraction of the price of a new unit , the rims and tires and the turbostuff (with engine?) and sell the donorcars for either scrap or as parts
most budget builders spend a lot of time working to collect the cash needed for the next stage in their build , so they have time to browse through the used car websites for bargains
a lot of the stuff from the yaris can be used in another project , like the ecu some of the wiring (pigtails) for said ecu the injectors the intercooler and the wheels , these are exactly the type of stuff budget builders are hunting for and they whont take a lot away from the scrap value of the car
just take the stuff off , photograph it and sell it on ebay , might make a nice video to hand deliver the parts to the buyer carrying a camera and take a look at their project sofar

snippet.textDisplay: My only comment would be that it would smarter to put that kind of money into a better platform. You could spend as much or maybe less and end up with something faster. If you put 13K into a 80's mustang I bet you could get into the 11's or 10's, or make a really nice track car. I have seen too often people drop tons of money into a car, like a sebring coupe for instance and end up with something that wasn't much faster than it was stock. But hey, if you love your car and that is what you want to do go for it. Its your money after all. Just don't be mad when you get beat by a honda civic or a 79 camaro or something. I have been there. When I was young I put a bunch of work into a 72 buick skylark. In the end my buddies bone stock honda CRX didn't have any trouble keeping up with me lol. Granted, I didn't put 13K into with a super charger or anything though. I basically turned it into a Buick GS instead of a skylark.

snippet.textDisplay: You guys are sponsored by haltech. I get it. Nice. However, being from australia, and being that you mentioned how well piggybacking worked for your setup, and how its inferred that letting the stock ecu handle everything except when the car goes into boost, wouldn't covering a good piggyback computer do good by all your fans? Why should anyone pay 2-3 grand for a standalone engine management like haltech, motec, electromotive, etc. when you can have exactly that, WITH tons of features that a system like Dastek's Unichip offers? But even if you're not going to run them on your cars, because your sponsored by haltech, wouldn't it at least make sense to at least expose your fans to something like the unichip? I'm from the U.S. I have installed and tuned an electromotive tec2 in the past, back in 1999 on my saturn sc2, aftermarket turbo setup. Today, I don't want to have to install all that, tune for startup enrichments, decel enrichments, accel enrichments, and of course learn each standalone's unique fueling theory (holy cow-electromotives 'time on for one gamma'!!) when a system exists that pretty much cuts a lot of that down, and allows the factory ecu to handle all that other business. AND, in today's greta thunberg concious mindset, there is no check engine light on (unlike pirating all signals from all sensors and leaving the stock ecu for air con, etc to handle, thus generating a check engine light as it looks for its ait, clt sns, crank, etc). At any rate, being how large unichip seems to be in aussie land, can you do a segment on it, UNBIASED and give your fans some more of those mighty car mods to choose from, instead of one alone just due to sponsorship? As I'm sure you know, unichip has kits you install where you tell them the already installed upgrades, BUT, like what I'm going on the saturn I'm running today, I'm installing a blank and tuning it. Even in my instance, I don't have to tune startup, decel, accel, etc. but only when the engine sees boost do I have to mess with any timing and fueling. Thanks for all you do but just want you to do more and not be constricted by sponsorships.
